&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from [bold]IAM (Institute of Advanced Motorists)[bold] (WRT 016)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The IAM (Institute of Advanced Motorists) directly influences the driving and riding of more than 135,000 UK road users every year (full members, associates and commercial clients).  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Established in 1956, the IAM is best known for the advanced driving test and the advanced driving course.  The IAM has grown to become the UK’s largest road safety charity, dedicated to raising driving standards, engaging with the road-using public and inf
[normal]luencing road safety policy.  IAM Drive and Survive also provides a range of occupational driver training courses to the commercial market.  In January 2007, the IAM Policy and Research division was established to undertake consultation responses, campaign
[normal]ing and research to assist in the understanding of road safety issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our response is laid out below in the paragraph numbers supplied.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Overview[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The IAM welcomes this independent review and believes
[normal] 
[normal]the vast majority of road users, householders and bus
[normal]inesses would like to exercise their sense of personal responsibility when dealing with weather related issues.  The role of government, central and local, should be to allow them to make informed decisions and safely contribute to keeping the country movi
[normal]ng.
[normal] In summary our key suggestions are;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1[bold].[bold]              [bold]UKRLG Review and its recommendations[bold]&#xa0;[bold]No 
[normal]comment
