[normal]2.[bold]              [bold]The approach to winter resilience – highways[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]What has been the experience of your authority, organisation of the winter 2009-10, and what are the lessons you have learned?  If you have conducted a formal review we would be pleased to see a
[normal] copy
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Not applicable
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]What has been your own practice about salt stocks, and your experience of the salt supply chain?  What views do you have about the operation of the Salt Cell?
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The IAM believes that a ‘just in time’ approach
[normal] (
[normal]i.e.
[normal] only holding a 7 day reserve)
[normal] to something as crucial as salt stocks is not appropriate.  Stock should be held to deal with extreme weather conditions even if this requires the provision of more storage facilities alongside the road network.
[normal] 
[normal]We r
[normal]ecognise 
[normal]that there is a holding cost but a full cost benefit analysis should be undertaken.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Salt Cell
[normal] should c
[normal]ome into play earlier based on forecast
[normal]ing
[normal] and support local planning
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5
[normal]              
[normal]What action would you like to see taken by others – whether in relation to 
[normal]salt supply and use or to other matters?
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The IAM supports the provision of more local salt bins and salt supply points to allow d
[normal]r
[normal]ivers to clear their own drives and local roads.  Salt should be freely available and supplied in suitable bagged containers
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]It is not acceptable that salt is made available but often must be collected in your own container.  Salt bins at key locations should be replenished on a more frequent basis during periods of heavy use.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]T
[normal]he health and safety legislation 
[normal]surrounding 
[normal]the clearing of paths and roads 
[normal]must be 
[normal]clarified. 
[normal] Many believe that by taking responsibility for clearing snow and ice they become liable to prosecution for any resulting injuries or accidents on the area that they have cleared. This is stopping communit
[normal]ies helping themselves. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal]              
[normal]Should further action or powers be taken by central government or its agencies to assure salt supplies or winter resilience generally?
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Prepare for the worst and have salt s
[normal]tock levels 
[normal]to cover this so that 
[normal]sto
[normal]cks don’t redu
[normal]ce
[normal] to the levels they fell to last winter.  
[normal]Existing
[normal] powers, good planning and additional 
[normal]s
[normal]tor
[normal]a
[normal]ge 
[normal]facilities
[normal] shou
[normal]ld 
[normal]avoid the need for any 
[normal]additional
[normal] powers
[normal].
